  "prompt": "What are shadows, midtones and highlights?",
  "response": "In photography, graphic design, and image processing, shadows, midtones, and highlights refer to different tonal ranges in an image:\n\n1. Shadows\n- Darkest areas of an image\n- Represent the lowest light values\n- Located in areas with minimal light or no direct light\n- Typically appear deep black or dark gray\n\n2. Midtones\n- Middle range of tones between shadows and highlights\n- Represent average light levels\n- Contain most of the image's detail and color information\n- Appears as moderate gray tones\n\n3. Highlights\n- Brightest areas of an image\n- Represent the highest light values\n- Located where light directly hits an object or surface\n- Typically appear very bright white or light gray\n\nPhotographers and image editors often adjust these tonal ranges to:\n- Improve image contrast\n- Enhance detail\n- Correct exposure\n- Create specific visual effects\n- Balance overall image appearance\n\nDifferent editing tools like levels, curves, and tone mapping allow precise manipulation of these tonal ranges to achieve desired visual results.",
